# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: cointegration
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:cointegration/augmented-dickey-fuller-test] In statistics, an **augmented Dickey–Fuller test** (**ADF**) tests the null hypothesis that a unit root is present in a time series sample.
[src:cointegration/augmented-dickey-fuller-test] The alternative hypothesis depends on which version of the test is used, but is usually stationarity or trend-stationarity.
[src:cointegration/augmented-dickey-fuller-test] It is an augmented version of the Dickey–Fuller test for a larger and more complicated set of time series models.
[src:cointegration/augmented-dickey-fuller-test] The augmented Dickey–Fuller (ADF) statistic, used in the test, is a negative number.
[src:cointegration/augmented-dickey-fuller-test] The more negative it is, the stronger the rejection of the hypothesis that there is a unit root at some level of confidence.
[src:cointegration/augmented-dickey-fuller-test] where $\alpha$ is a constant, $\beta$ the coefficient on a time trend and p the lag order of the autoregressive process.
[src:cointegration/augmented-dickey-fuller-test] Imposing the constraints $\alpha =0$ and $\beta =0$ corresponds to modelling a random walk and using the constraint $\beta =0$ corresponds to modeling a random walk with a drift.
[src:cointegration/augmented-dickey-fuller-test] Consequently, there are three main versions of the test, analogous those of the Dickey–Fuller test.
[src:cointegration/augmented-dickey-fuller-test] By including lags of the order *p*, the ADF formulation allows for higher-order autoregressive processes.
[src:cointegration/augmented-dickey-fuller-test] This means that the lag length *p* must be determined in order to use the test.
[src:cointegration/augmented-dickey-fuller-test] One approach to doing this is to test down from high orders and examine the *t*-values on coefficients.
[src:cointegration/augmented-dickey-fuller-test] An alternative approach is to examine information criteria such as the Akaike information criterion, Bayesian information criterion or the Hannan–Quinn information criterion.
[src:cointegration/augmented-dickey-fuller-test] is computed, it can be compared to the relevant critical value for the Dickey–Fuller test.
[src:cointegration/augmented-dickey-fuller-test] As this test is asymmetric, we are only concerned with negative values of our test statistic $\mathrm {DF} _{\tau }$ .
[src:cointegration/augmented-dickey-fuller-test] If the calculated test statistic is less (more negative) than the critical value, then the null hypothesis of $\gamma =0$ is rejected and no unit root is present.
[src:cointegration/augmented-dickey-fuller-test] The intuition behind the test is that if the series is characterised by a unit root process, then the lagged level of the series ( $y_{t-1}$ ) will provide no relevant information in predicting the change in $y_{t}$ besides the one obtained in the lagged changes ( $\Delta y_{t-k}$ ).
[src:cointegration/augmented-dickey-fuller-test] In this case, the $\gamma =0$ and null hypothesis is not rejected.
[src:cointegration/augmented-dickey-fuller-test] In contrast, when the process has no unit root, it is stationary and hence exhibits reversion to the mean - so the lagged level will provide relevant information in predicting the change of the series and the null hypothesis of a unit root will be rejected.
[src:cointegration/augmented-dickey-fuller-test] A model that includes a constant and a time trend is estimated using sample of 50 observations and yields the $\mathrm {DF} _{\tau }$ statistic of −4.57.
[src:cointegration/augmented-dickey-fuller-test] This is more negative than the tabulated critical value of −3.50, so at the 95% level, the null hypothesis of a unit root will be rejected.
[src:cointegration/augmented-dickey-fuller-test] There are alternative unit root tests such as the Phillips–Perron test (PP) or the ADF-GLS test procedure (ERS) developed by Elliott, Rothenberg and Stock (1996).
[src:cointegration/cointegration] In econometrics, **cointegration** is a statistical property that describes a long-run equilibrium relationship among two or more time series variables, even if the individual series are non-stationary (i.e., they contain stochastic trends).
[src:cointegration/cointegration] In such cases, the variables may drift in the short run, but their linear combination is stationary, implying that they move together over time and remain bound by a stable equilibrium.
[src:cointegration/cointegration] More formally, if several time series are individually integrated of order *d* (meaning they require *d* differences to become stationary) but a linear combination of them is integrated of a lower order, then those time series are said to be cointegrated.
[src:cointegration/cointegration] That is, if (*X*,*Y*,*Z*) are each integrated of order *d*, and there exist coefficients *a*,*b*,*c* such that *aX* + *bY* + *cZ* is integrated of order less than d, then *X*, *Y*, and *Z* are cointegrated.
[src:cointegration/cointegration] Cointegration is a crucial concept in time series analysis, particularly when dealing with variables that exhibit trends, such as macroeconomic data.
[src:cointegration/cointegration] In an influential paper, Charles Nelson and Charles Plosser (1982) provided statistical evidence that many US macroeconomic time series (like GNP, wages, employment, etc.) have stochastic trends.
[src:cointegration/cointegration] If two or more series are individually integrated (in the time series sense) but some linear combination of them has a lower order of integration, then the series are said to be cointegrated.
[src:cointegration/cointegration] A common example is where the individual series are first-order integrated (⁠ $I(1)$ ⁠) but some (cointegrating) vector of coefficients exists to form a stationary linear combination of them.
[src:cointegration/cointegration] The first to introduce and analyse the concept of spurious—or nonsense—regression was Udny Yule in 1926.
[src:cointegration/cointegration] Granger's 1987 paper with Robert Engle formalized the cointegrating vector approach, and coined the term.
[src:cointegration/cointegration] For integrated ⁠ $I(1)$ ⁠ processes, Granger and Newbold showed that de-trending does not work to eliminate the problem of spurious correlation, and that the superior alternative is to check for co-integration.
[src:cointegration/cointegration] Two series with ⁠ $I(1)$ ⁠ trends can be co-integrated only if there is a genuine relationship between the two.
[src:cointegration/cointegration] Thus the standard current methodology for time series regressions is to check all-time series involved for integration.
[src:cointegration/cointegration] If there are ⁠ $I(1)$ ⁠ series on both sides of the regression relationship, then it is possible for regressions to give misleading results.
[src:cointegration/cointegration] The possible presence of cointegration must be taken into account when choosing a technique to test hypotheses concerning the relationship between two variables having unit roots (i.e. integrated of at least order one).
[src:cointegration/cointegration] The usual procedure for testing hypotheses concerning the relationship between non-stationary variables was to run ordinary least squares (OLS) regressions on data which had been differenced.
[src:cointegration/cointegration] This method is biased if the non-stationary variables are cointegrated.
[src:cointegration/cointegration] For example, regressing the consumption series for any country (e.g.
[src:cointegration/cointegration] Fiji) against the GNP for a randomly selected dissimilar country (e.g.
[src:cointegration/cointegration] Afghanistan) might give a high R-squared relationship (suggesting high explanatory power on Fiji's consumption from Afghanistan's GNP).
[src:cointegration/cointegration] This is called spurious regression: two integrated ⁠ $I(1)$ ⁠ series which are not directly causally related may nonetheless show a significant correlation.
[src:cointegration/cointegration] If $x_{t}$ and $y_{t}$ both have order of integration *d*=1 and are cointegrated, then a linear combination of them must be stationary for some value of $\beta$ and $u_{t}$ .
[src:cointegration/cointegration] If $\beta$ is known, we can test $u_{t}$ for stationarity with an augmented Dickey–Fuller test or Phillips–Perron test.
[src:cointegration/cointegration] If $\beta$ is unknown, we must first estimate it.
[src:cointegration/cointegration] This is typically done by using ordinary least squares (by regressing $y_{t}$ on $x_{t}$ and an intercept).
[src:cointegration/cointegration] Then, we can run an ADF test on $u_{t}$ .
[src:cointegration/cointegration] However, when $\beta$ is estimated, the critical values of this ADF test are non-standard, and increase in absolute value as more regressors are included.
[src:cointegration/cointegration] If the variables are found to be cointegrated, a second-stage regression is conducted.
[src:cointegration/cointegration] This is a regression of $\Delta y_{t}$ on the lagged regressors, $\Delta x_{t}$ and the lagged residuals from the first stage, ${\hat {u}}_{t-1}$ .
[src:cointegration/cointegration] The Johansen test is a test for cointegration that allows for more than one cointegrating relationship, unlike the Engle–Granger method, but this test is subject to asymptotic properties, i.e. large samples.
[src:cointegration/cointegration] If the sample size is too small then the results will not be reliable and one should use Auto Regressive Distributed Lags (ARDL).
[src:cointegration/cointegration] Phillips and Sam Ouliaris (1990) show that residual-based unit root tests applied to the estimated cointegrating residuals do not have the usual Dickey–Fuller distributions under the null hypothesis of no-cointegration.
[src:cointegration/cointegration] Because of the spurious regression phenomenon under the null hypothesis, the distribution of these tests have asymptotic distributions that depend on (1) the number of deterministic trend terms and (2) the number of variables with which co-integration is being tested.
[src:cointegration/cointegration] These distributions are known as Phillips–Ouliaris distributions and critical values have been tabulated.
[src:cointegration/cointegration] In finite samples, a superior alternative to the use of these asymptotic critical value is to generate critical values from simulations.
[src:cointegration/cointegration] In practice, cointegration is often used for two ⁠ $I(1)$ ⁠ series, but it is more generally applicable and can be used for variables integrated of higher order (to detect correlated accelerations or other second-difference effects).
[src:cointegration/cointegration] **Multicointegration** extends the cointegration technique beyond two variables, and occasionally to variables integrated at different orders.
[src:cointegration/cointegration] Tests for cointegration assume that the cointegrating vector is constant during the period of study.
[src:cointegration/cointegration] In reality, it is possible that the long-run relationship between the underlying variables change (shifts in the cointegrating vector can occur).
[src:cointegration/cointegration] The reason for this might be technological progress, economic crises, changes in the people's preferences and behaviour accordingly, policy or regime alteration, and organizational or institutional developments.
[src:cointegration/cointegration] This is especially likely to be the case if the sample period is long.
[src:cointegration/cointegration] To take this issue into account, tests have been introduced for cointegration with one unknown structural break, and tests for cointegration with two unknown breaks are also available.
[src:cointegration/cointegration] Several Bayesian methods have been proposed to compute the posterior distribution of the number of cointegrating relationships and the cointegrating linear combinations.
[src:cointegration/error-correction-model] An **error correction model** (**ECM**) is a type of time series model commonly applied when the underlying variables share a long-run stochastic trend, a property known as cointegration.
[src:cointegration/error-correction-model] ECMs provide a theoretically grounded framework for estimating both short-run dynamics and long-run relationships among variables.
[src:cointegration/error-correction-model] The term *error correction* refers to the idea that deviations from the long-run equilibrium (the *error*) affect short-run adjustments.
[src:cointegration/error-correction-model] In this framework, the model directly estimates the speed at which a dependent variable returns to equilibrium following changes in other explanatory variables.
[src:cointegration/error-correction-model] Yule (1926) and Granger and Newbold (1974) were the first to draw attention to the problem of spurious correlation and find solutions on how to address it in time series analysis.
[src:cointegration/error-correction-model] Ordinary least squares will no longer be consistent and commonly used test-statistics will be non-valid.
[src:cointegration/error-correction-model] In particular, Monte Carlo simulations show that one will get a very high R squared, very high individual t-statistic and a low Durbin–Watson statistic.
[src:cointegration/error-correction-model] Technically speaking, Phillips (1986) proved that parameter estimates will not converge in probability, the intercept will diverge and the slope will have a non-degenerate distribution as the sample size increases.
[src:cointegration/error-correction-model] However, there might be a common stochastic trend to both series that a researcher is genuinely interested in because it reflects a long-run relationship between these variables.
[src:cointegration/error-correction-model] Because of the stochastic nature of the trend it is not possible to break up integrated series into a deterministic (predictable) trend and a stationary series containing deviations from trend.
[src:cointegration/error-correction-model] Even in deterministically detrended random walks spurious correlations will eventually emerge.
[src:cointegration/error-correction-model] Thus detrending does not solve the estimation problem.
[src:cointegration/error-correction-model] In order to still use the Box–Jenkins approach, one could difference the series and then estimate models such as ARIMA, given that many commonly used time series (e.g. in economics) appear to be stationary in first differences.
[src:cointegration/error-correction-model] Forecasts from such a model will still reflect cycles and seasonality that are present in the data.
[src:cointegration/error-correction-model] However, any information about long-run adjustments that the data in levels may contain is omitted and longer term forecasts will be unreliable.
[src:cointegration/error-correction-model] This led Sargan (1964) to develop the ECM methodology, which retains the level information.
[src:cointegration/error-correction-model] Several methods are known in the literature for estimating a refined dynamic model as described above.
[src:cointegration/error-correction-model] Among these are the Engle and Granger 2-step approach, estimating their ECM in one step and the vector-based VECM using Johansen's method.
[src:cointegration/error-correction-model] The first step of this method is to pre-test the individual time series used, to confirm that they are non-stationary in the first place.
[src:cointegration/error-correction-model] This can be done by standard unit root DF testing and ADF test (to resolve the problem of serially correlated errors).
[src:cointegration/error-correction-model] Take the case of two different series $x_{t}$ and $y_{t}$ .
[src:cointegration/error-correction-model] If both are I(0), standard regression analysis will be valid.
[src:cointegration/error-correction-model] If they are integrated of a different order, e.g. one being I(1) and the other being I(0), we have to transform the model.
[src:cointegration/error-correction-model] The second step is then to estimate the model using ordinary least squares: $y_{t}=\beta _{0}+\beta _{1}x_{t}+\varepsilon _{t}$ If the regression is not spurious as determined by test criteria described above, Ordinary least squares will not only be valid, but also consistent (Stock, 1987).
[src:cointegration/error-correction-model] We can then test for cointegration using a standard t-statistic on $\alpha$ .
[src:cointegration/error-correction-model] The Engle–Granger approach as described above suffers from a number of weaknesses.
[src:cointegration/error-correction-model] Namely it is restricted to only a single equation with one variable designated as the dependent variable, explained by another variable that is assumed to be weakly exogeneous for the parameters of interest.
[src:cointegration/error-correction-model] It also relies on pretesting the time series to find out whether variables are I(0) or I(1).
[src:cointegration/error-correction-model] These weaknesses can be addressed through the use of Johansen's procedure.
[src:cointegration/error-correction-model] Its advantages include that pretesting is not necessary, there can be numerous cointegrating relationships, all variables are treated as endogenous and tests relating to the long-run parameters are possible.
[src:cointegration/error-correction-model] The resulting model is known as a vector error correction model (VECM), as it adds error correction features to a multi-factor model known as vector autoregression (VAR).
[src:cointegration/error-correction-model] The idea of cointegration may be demonstrated in a simple macroeconomic setting.
[src:cointegration/error-correction-model] Suppose, consumption $C_{t}$ and disposable income $Y_{t}$ are macroeconomic time series that are related in the long run (see Permanent income hypothesis).
[src:cointegration/error-correction-model] Specifically, let average propensity to consume be 90%, that is, in the long run $C_{t}=0.9Y_{t}$ .
[src:cointegration/error-correction-model] From the econometrician's point of view, this long run relationship (aka cointegration) exists if errors from the regression $C_{t}=\beta Y_{t}+\varepsilon _{t}$ are a stationary series, although $Y_{t}$ and $C_{t}$ are non-stationary.
[src:cointegration/error-correction-model] Suppose also that if $Y_{t}$ suddenly changes by $\Delta Y_{t}$ , then $C_{t}$ changes by $\Delta C_{t}=0.5\,\Delta Y_{t}$ , that is, marginal propensity to consume equals 50%.
[src:cointegration/error-correction-model] Our final assumption is that the gap between current and equilibrium consumption decreases each period by 20%.
[src:cointegration/error-correction-model] To see how the model works, consider two kinds of shocks: permanent and transitory (temporary).
[src:cointegration/error-correction-model] For simplicity, let $\varepsilon _{t}$ be zero for all t.
[src:cointegration/error-correction-model] Suppose that in the period t, disposable income $Y_{t}$ increases by 10 and then returns to its previous level.
[src:cointegration/error-correction-model] Then $C_{t}$ first (in period t) increases by 5 (half of 10), but after the second period $C_{t}$ begins to decrease and converges to its initial level.
[src:cointegration/error-correction-model] In contrast, if the shock to $Y_{t}$ is permanent, then $C_{t}$ slowly converges to a value that exceeds the initial $C_{t-1}$ by 9.
[src:cointegration/error-correction-model] This structure is common to all ECM models.
[src:cointegration/error-correction-model] In practice, econometricians often first estimate the cointegration relationship (equation in levels), and then insert it into the main model (equation in differences).
[src:cointegration/johansen-test] In statistics, the **Johansen test**, named after Søren Johansen, is a procedure for testing cointegration of several, say *k*, I(1) time series.
[src:cointegration/johansen-test] This test permits more than one cointegrating relationship so is more generally applicable than the Engle-Granger test which is based on the Dickey–Fuller (or the augmented) test for unit roots in the residuals from a single (estimated) cointegrating relationship.
[src:cointegration/johansen-test] There are two types of Johansen test, either with trace or with eigenvalue, and the inferences might be a little bit different.
[src:cointegration/johansen-test] The null hypothesis for the trace test is that the number of cointegration vectors is *r* = *r** < *k*, vs. the alternative that *r* = *k*.
[src:cointegration/johansen-test] Testing proceeds sequentially for *r** = 1,2, etc. and the first non-rejection of the null is taken as an estimate of *r*.
[src:cointegration/johansen-test] The null hypothesis for the "maximum eigenvalue" test is as for the trace test but the alternative is *r* = *r** + 1 and, again, testing proceeds sequentially for *r** = 1,2,etc., with the first non-rejection used as an estimator for *r*.
[src:cointegration/johansen-test] Just like a unit root test, there can be a constant term, a trend term, both, or neither in the model.
[src:cointegration/johansen-test] Inferences are drawn on Π, and they will be the same, so is the explanatory power.
[src:cointegration/spurious-relationship] An example of a spurious relationship can be found in the time-series literature, where a spurious regression is one that provides misleading statistical evidence of a linear relationship between independent non-stationary variables.
[src:cointegration/spurious-relationship] In fact, the non-stationarity may be due to the presence of a unit root in both variables.
[src:cointegration/spurious-relationship] In particular, any two nominal economic variables are likely to be correlated with each other, even when neither has a causal effect on the other, because each equals a real variable times the price level, and the common presence of the price level in the two data series imparts correlation to them.
[src:cointegration/spurious-relationship] Another example of a spurious relationship can be seen by examining a city's ice cream sales.
[src:cointegration/spurious-relationship] The sales might be highest when the rate of drownings in city swimming pools is highest.
[src:cointegration/spurious-relationship] To allege that ice cream sales cause drowning, or vice versa, would be to imply a spurious relationship between the two.
[src:cointegration/spurious-relationship] In reality, a heat wave may have caused both.
[src:cointegration/spurious-relationship] The heat wave is an example of a hidden or unseen variable, also known as a confounding variable.
[src:cointegration/spurious-relationship] Another commonly noted example is a series of Dutch statistics showing a positive correlation between the number of storks nesting in a series of springs and the number of human babies born at that time.
[src:cointegration/spurious-relationship] Of course there was no causal connection; they were correlated with each other only because of two independent coincidences.
[src:cointegration/spurious-relationship] During the Pagan era, which can be traced back at least to medieval times more than 600 years ago, it was common for couples to wed during the annual summer solstice, because summer was associated with fertility.
[src:cointegration/spurious-relationship] At the same time, storks would commence their annual migration, flying all the way from Europe to Africa.
[src:cointegration/spurious-relationship] The birds would then return the following spring — exactly nine months later.
[src:cointegration/spurious-relationship] For 16 consecutive elections between 1940 and 2000, the Redskins Rule correctly matched whether the incumbent President's political party would retain or lose the Presidency.
[src:cointegration/spurious-relationship] The rule eventually failed shortly after Elias Sports Bureau discovered the correlation in 2000; in 2004, 2012 and 2016, the results of the Commanders' game and the election did not match.
[src:cointegration/spurious-relationship] Often one tests a null hypothesis of no correlation between two variables, and chooses in advance to reject the hypothesis if the correlation computed from a data sample would have occurred in less than (say) 5% of data samples if the null hypothesis were true.
[src:cointegration/spurious-relationship] While a true null hypothesis will be accepted 95% of the time, the other 5% of the times having a true null of no correlation a zero correlation will be wrongly rejected, causing acceptance of a correlation which is spurious (an event known as Type I error).
[src:cointegration/spurious-relationship] Here the spurious correlation in the sample resulted from random selection of a sample that did not reflect the true properties of the underlying population.
[src:cointegration/spurious-relationship] The term "spurious relationship" is commonly used in statistics and in particular in experimental research techniques, both of which attempt to understand and predict direct causal relationships (X → Y).
[src:cointegration/spurious-relationship] A non-causal correlation can be spuriously created by an antecedent which causes both (W → X and W → Y).
[src:cointegration/spurious-relationship] Mediating variables, (X → M → Y), if undetected, estimate a total effect rather than direct effect without adjustment for the mediating variable M.
[src:cointegration/spurious-relationship] Because of this, experimentally identified correlations do not represent causal relationships unless spurious relationships can be ruled out.
[src:cointegration/spurious-relationship] In experiments, spurious relationships can often be identified by controlling for other factors, including those that have been theoretically identified as possible confounding factors.
[src:cointegration/spurious-relationship] For example, consider a researcher trying to determine whether a new drug kills bacteria; when the researcher applies the drug to a bacterial culture, the bacteria die.
[src:cointegration/spurious-relationship] But to help in ruling out the presence of a confounding variable, another culture is subjected to conditions that are as nearly identical as possible to those facing the first-mentioned culture, but the second culture is not subjected to the drug.
[src:cointegration/spurious-relationship] If there is an unseen confounding factor in those conditions, this control culture will die as well, so that no conclusion of efficacy of the drug can be drawn from the results of the first culture.
[src:cointegration/spurious-relationship] On the other hand, if the control culture does not die, then the researcher cannot reject the hypothesis that the drug is efficacious.
[src:cointegration/spurious-relationship] Disciplines whose data are mostly non-experimental, such as economics, usually employ observational data to establish causal relationships.
[src:cointegration/spurious-relationship] The body of statistical techniques used in economics is called econometrics.
[src:cointegration/spurious-relationship] The main statistical method in econometrics is multivariable regression analysis.
[src:cointegration/spurious-relationship] If there is reason to believe that none of the $x_{j}$ s is caused by *y*, then estimates of the coefficients $a_{j}$ are obtained.
[src:cointegration/spurious-relationship] If the null hypothesis that $a_{j}=0$ is rejected, then the alternative hypothesis that $a_{j}\neq 0$ and equivalently that $x_{j}$ causes *y* cannot be rejected.
[src:cointegration/spurious-relationship] On the other hand, if the null hypothesis that $a_{j}=0$ cannot be rejected, then equivalently the hypothesis of no causal effect of $x_{j}$ on *y* cannot be rejected.
[src:cointegration/spurious-relationship] Likewise, a change in $x_{j}$ is *not necessary* to change *y*, because a change in *y* could be caused by something implicit in the error term (or by some other causative explanatory variable included in the model).
[src:cointegration/spurious-relationship] Regression analysis controls for other relevant variables by including them as regressors (explanatory variables).
[src:cointegration/spurious-relationship] In addition, the use of multivariate regression helps to avoid wrongly inferring that an indirect effect of, say *x*1 (e.g., *x*1 → *x*2 → *y*) is a direct effect (*x*1 → *y*).
[src:cointegration/spurious-relationship] Just as an experimenter must be careful to employ an experimental design that controls for every confounding factor, so also must the user of multiple regression be careful to control for all confounding factors by including them among the regressors.
[src:cointegration/spurious-relationship] If a confounding factor is omitted from the regression, its effect is captured in the error term by default, and if the resulting error term is correlated with one (or more) of the included regressors, then the estimated regression may be biased or inconsistent (see omitted variable bias).
[src:cointegration/spurious-relationship] In addition to regression analysis, the data can be examined to determine if Granger causality exists.
[src:cointegration/spurious-relationship] The presence of Granger causality indicates both that *x* precedes *y*, and that *x* contains unique information about *y*.
[src:cointegration/spurious-relationship] There are several other relationships defined in statistical analysis as follows.
[src:cointegration/unit-root] In probability theory and statistics, a **unit root** is a property of certain stochastic processes (such as a random walk) that can create challenges for statistical inference in time series models.
[src:cointegration/unit-root] A linear stochastic process contains a unit root if 1 is a solution to its characteristic equation.
[src:cointegration/unit-root] Processes with a unit root are non-stationary, because they do not necessarily exhibit a deterministic trend.
[src:cointegration/unit-root] If the other roots of the characteristic equation lie inside the unit circle—that is, have a modulus (absolute value) less than one—then the first difference of the process will be stationary; otherwise, the process will need to be differenced multiple times to become stationary.
[src:cointegration/unit-root] If there are *d* unit roots, the process will have to be differenced *d* times in order to make it stationary.
[src:cointegration/unit-root] Unit root processes may sometimes be confused with trend-stationary processes; while they share many properties, they are different in many aspects.
[src:cointegration/unit-root] It is possible for a time series to be non-stationary, yet have no unit root and be trend-stationary.
[src:cointegration/unit-root] If a root of the process's characteristic equation is larger than 1, then it is called an **explosive process**, even though such processes are sometimes inaccurately called unit roots processes.
[src:cointegration/unit-root] The presence of a unit root can be tested using a unit root test.
[src:cointegration/unit-root] Here, $(\varepsilon _{t},t=0,1,2,\ldots ,)$ is a serially uncorrelated, zero-mean stochastic process with constant variance $\sigma ^{2}$ .
[src:cointegration/unit-root] then the stochastic process has a **unit root** or, alternatively, is integrated of order one, denoted $I(1)$ .
[src:cointegration/unit-root] If *m* = 1 is a root of multiplicity *r*, then the stochastic process is integrated of order *r*, denoted *I*(*r*).
[src:cointegration/unit-root] In this example, the characteristic equation is $m-a_{1}=0$ .
[src:cointegration/unit-root] If the process has a unit root, then it is a non-stationary time series.
[src:cointegration/unit-root] That is, the moments of the stochastic process depend on t .
[src:cointegration/unit-root] The variance of the series is diverging to infinity with *t*.
[src:cointegration/unit-root] The finite sample properties of regression models with first order ARMA errors, including unit roots, have been analyzed.
[src:cointegration/unit-root] Often, ordinary least squares (OLS) is used to estimate the slope coefficients of the autoregressive model.
[src:cointegration/unit-root] Use of OLS relies on the stochastic process being stationary.
[src:cointegration/unit-root] When the stochastic process is non-stationary, the use of OLS can produce invalid estimates.
[src:cointegration/unit-root] Granger and Newbold called such estimates 'spurious regression' results: high R2 values and high t-ratios yielding results with no real (in their context, economic) meaning.
[src:cointegration/unit-root] To estimate the slope coefficients, one should first conduct a unit root test, whose null hypothesis is that a unit root is present.
[src:cointegration/unit-root] If that hypothesis is rejected, one can use OLS.
[src:cointegration/unit-root] However, if the presence of a unit root is not rejected, then one should apply the difference operator to the series.
[src:cointegration/unit-root] If another unit root test shows the differenced time series to be stationary, OLS can then be applied to this series to estimate the slope coefficients.
[src:cointegration/unit-root] OLS can be used to estimate the slope coefficient, $\lambda _{1}$ .
[src:cointegration/unit-root] If the process has multiple unit roots, the difference operator can be applied multiple times.
[src:cointegration/unit-root] Economists debate whether various economic statistics, especially output, have a unit root or are trend-stationary.
[src:cointegration/unit-root] where *c* is a constant term referred to as the "drift" term, and $e_{t}$ is white noise.
[src:cointegration/unit-root] Any non-zero value of the noise term, occurring for only one period, will permanently affect the value of $y_{t}$ as shown in the graph, so deviations from the line $y_{t}=a+ct$ are non-stationary; there is no reversion to any trend line.
[src:cointegration/unit-root] where *k* is the slope of the trend and $u_{t}$ is noise (white noise in the simplest case; more generally, noise following its own stationary autoregressive process).
[src:cointegration/unit-root] Here any transient noise will not alter the long-run tendency for $y_{t}$ to be on the trend line, as also shown in the graph.
[src:cointegration/unit-root] This process is said to be trend-stationary because deviations from the trend line are stationary.
[src:cointegration/unit-root] The issue is particularly popular in the literature on business cycles.
[src:cointegration/unit-root] Research on the subject began with Nelson and Plosser whose paper on GNP and other output aggregates failed to reject the unit root hypothesis for these series.
[src:cointegration/unit-root] Since then, a debate—entwined with technical disputes on statistical methods—has ensued.
[src:cointegration/unit-root] Some economists argue that GDP has a unit root or structural break, implying that economic downturns result in permanently lower GDP levels in the long run.
[src:cointegration/unit-root] Other economists argue that GDP is trend-stationary: That is, when GDP dips below trend during a downturn it later returns to the level implied by the trend so that there is no permanent decrease in output.
[src:cointegration/unit-root] While the literature on the unit root hypothesis may consist of arcane debate on statistical methods, the hypothesis carries significant practical implications for economic forecasts and policies.
